			<translation>
				Better the aphorisms of Diogenes and Aristippus than those of Aristotle or Plato. 
				Just as Demades is funnier than Demosthenes himself.
				And Aesop too, many years before Pythagoras. But no Roman was
				wittier than Cicero, not even Caesar. Just as he who wants to be
				like Cicero or Caesar must be by far the wittiest. Even those exquisite orators
				were immensely witty and funny: Proaeresius, Libanius, Julian, Eunapius,
				the Delitiae Atticae. Just as, much earlie, Attic salt was sweeter than	<!-- CG: I think Delitiae Atticae is a book, but I can only find it published first in 1624, which is a bit too late. --> <!--JG: Hmm, I can't find anything else either. Will leave this as an open question-->
				Hymettian honey itself.	
			</translation>
